Here’s what caught our attention on Tuesday: 1.Q2 GDP South Africa’s gross domestic profit (GDP) for the second quarter will be released on Tuesday. In the first quarter of 2018, South Africa’s GDP contracted by 2.2%, reinforcing negative sentiment on South Africa’s economic outlook. Update to follow. 2.Discovery results One of South Africa’s largest financial services firms, Discovery is reporting a 16% increase in normalised headline earnings to R5.4 billion for the year ended June 30, 2018. The company’s normalised profit from operations also increased 17% to R8.2 billion. Discovery generated R2 billion in new initiatives, while the growth in value of new business was 16%. The board is declaring a final gross cash dividend of 501.91 cents for the period. 3.Libstar results Packaged foods company, which listed on the JSE recently is reporting its results for the six months ended June 30, 2018. Since listing, it raised R3 billion in primary and secondary capital. Libstar’s revenue increased 14.2% to R4.5 billion. Earnings per share and headline earnings per share from continuing operations fell to 13 cents from 25 cents in the first half of 2018. The company says sales are being boosted mainly by its Lancewood brand. The company has resolved that no dividend will be declared for the period. 4.Aspen Pharmacare trading statement Pharmaceutical company, Aspen issued a trading statement for the year ended June 30, 2018. The company says it expects normalised headline earnings per share to increase between 8% and 12% to 1580.3 cents and 1638.8 cents, it also expects headline earnings per share to increase between 11% and 15% to 1442.4 cents and 1494.4 cents. Results are expected to be released on September 13, 2018. 5.WBHO results Construction engineering company, WBHO is reporting an 8.1% increase in headline earnings per share to R1.4 billion for the year ended June 30, 2018. WBHO says locally building activity is on the decrease due to low public infrastructure spending, furthermore, its construction plans in the rest of Africa remained ‘relatively stagnant’. The board has resolved to declare a dividend of 475 cents per share for the period.